VALUES ('781e5dd6-3da2-5399-89bd-cc58e6d387b4', 'UTUMISHI GIRLS ACADEMY DORMITORY FIRE', 'Gilgil, Nakuru County', 'May 28, 2026', 'Fire Disaster', 'advanced', 'At approximately 3:30 AM on May 28, 2026, a devastating fire broke out in a dormitory at Utumishi Girls Academy in Gilgil, Nakuru County, approximately 120 km (76 miles) northwest of Nairobi.', '{"rawText": "CASE STUDY 2: UTUMISHI GIRLS ACADEMY DORMITORY FIRE\nGilgil, Nakuru County - May 28, 2026\nIncident Background\nAt approximately 3:30 AM on May 28, 2026, a devastating fire broke out in a dormitory at Utumishi Girls Academy in Gilgil, Nakuru County, approximately 120 km (76 miles) northwest of Nairobi. \n\nIncident Statistics:\n\n16 confirmed fatalities (students)\n\n79 injured students requiring medical attention\n\n220 students in the dormitory when the fire started\n\nResponse time: First responders arrived approximately 2 hours after the fire was reported\n\nSchool Fire Context (Kenya)\n2024: 21 boys killed in a dormitory fire at Hillside Endarasha Academy, Nyeri County\n\n2017: 10 students died in a dormitory fire at Moi Girls High School in Nairobi\n\n2001: 67 students died in the deadliest school fire in Kenya''s history at Kyanguli Secondary School\n\n2022 Auditor General Report: Found most state secondary schools were not prepared to deal with fires\n\nPart 1: Dispatch Information\nYou receive the following dispatch message:\n\n\"MAJOR INCIDENT - STRUCTURE FIRE - UTUMISHI GIRLS ACADEMY, GILGIL, NAKURU COUNTY.\n\nConfirmed: Dormitory fire with multiple casualties. Students trapped. Jumpers reported.\n\nMulti-agency response: County Fire Brigade, County Disaster Response Teams, Kenya Red Cross, National Police Service.\n\nRespond immediately. Stage at the school entrance. Be prepared for mass casualty triage.\"\n\n\ud83d\uded1 STUDENT ACTION REQUIRED - PHASE 1\n1. Dispatch & Response Assessment:\n\nYour Response: (fill in)\n\ntext\nTime to scene (estimated distance 30 km): ________________________________\nInitial patient count estimate: __________________________________________\nResources you are bringing: _____________________________________________\nWhat additional resources should be requested immediately? _______________\n2. Safety & Scene Considerations:\n\nYour Response: (fill in)\n\ntext\nSafety concerns: ________________________________________________________\nBSI precautions: ________________________________________________________\nTriage considerations: __________________________________________________\nPart 2: Arrival at Scene\nYou arrive at the school approximately 45 minutes after dispatch. The scene is chaotic: \n\nFire: The dormitory fire is still burning. Three fire engines are on scene but have difficulty accessing the building.\n\nStudents: Injured students are everywhere. Some are lying on the ground, others are being carried by teachers and fellow students.\n\nParents: Dozens of parents have already arrived, frantically searching for their children.\n\nSecurity: Police have established a perimeter, but it is not fully secure.\n\nOther Responders: Kenya Red Cross personnel are on scene but appear overwhelmed.\n\nPatients observed:\n\nPatient\tAge/Sex\tInjuries\tStatus\n1\t15/F\tBurns to arms and face, singed hair, RR 30, HR 110\tConscious, in severe distress\n2\t17/F\tBurn injuries to >50% of body, RR 36, HR 140, BP 85/50\tSemi-conscious, severe respiratory distress\n3\t16/F\tFractured leg from jumping, open fracture tibia, RR 22, HR 110\tConscious, in pain, BP 110/70\n4\t16/F\tUnresponsive, not breathing, visible burns\tApneic, pulseless\n5\t18/F\tSmoke inhalation, coughing, O2 sat 90%, RR 30\tConscious, anxious\n6\t15/F\tMultiple lacerations from glass, bleeding, RR 24, HR 100\tConscious, BP 110/70\n7\t17/F\tSecond-degree burns to both hands, RR 25, HR 115\tConscious, anxious\n\ud83d\uded1 STUDENT ACTION REQUIRED - PHASE 2\n3. Triage & Initial Assessment:\n\nYour Response: (fill in)\n\ntext\nPatient 1 (15/F, burns to arms/face, RR 30, HR 110):\nColor: _______________ Priority: _______________\nInterventions: ___________________________________________________________\n\nPatient 2 (17/F, >50% burns, RR 36, HR 140, BP 85/50):\nColor: _______________ Priority: _______________\nInterventions: ___________________________________________________________\n\nPatient 3 (16/F, open fracture tibia, RR 22, HR 110):\nColor: _______________ Priority: _______________\nInterventions: ___________________________________________________________\n\nPatient 4 (16/F, unresponsive, apneic, pulseless):\nColor: _______________ Priority: _______________\nInterventions: ___________________________________________________________\n\nPatient 5 (18/F, smoke inhalation, RR 30, O2 sat 90%):\nColor: _______________ Priority: _______________\nInterventions: ___________________________________________________________\n\nPatient 6 (15/F, lacerations, RR 24, HR 100):\nColor: _______________ Priority: _______________\nInterventions: ___________________________________________________________\n\nPatient 7 (17/F, hand burns, RR 25, HR 115):\nColor: _______________ Priority: _______________\nInterventions: ___________________________________________________________\n4. Critical Decision: Burn Triage:\n\nYour Response: (fill in)\n\ntext\nFor Patient 2 (17/F, >50% burns, BP 85/50, RR 36):\n- Rule of Nines estimate: ________________________________________________\n- Critical burn criteria: ________________________________________________\n- Transport priority: ____________________________________________________\n- Most likely complications: _____________________________________________\n\nFor Patient 7 (17/F, hand burns):\n- Burn severity: ________________________________________________________\n- Critical burn? Why/why not: ___________________________________________\n- Special considerations: ________________________________________________\n\ud83d\udcca EVALUATION SCORING\nSection\tComponent\tPoints\tCriteria\nPhase 1\tDispatch Assessment\t10\tCorrect identification of response needs\nPhase 1\tSafety Considerations\t10\tAppropriate scene safety protocols\nPhase 2\tTriage Accuracy\t15\tCorrect START triage classification\nPhase 2\tBurn Triage\t10\tAccurate burn severity assessment\nPhase 3\tTransport Planning\t15\tEffective resource allocation\nPhase 3\tCommunication\t10\tAppropriate hospital notification\nPhase 4\tLessons Learned\t10\tInsightful analysis of failures\nTOTAL\t\t80\t\nPassing Score: 60/80 (75%)", "sourceHeading": "CASE STUDY 2: UTUMISHI GIRLS ACADEMY DORMITORY FIRE", "locationLine": "Gilgil, Nakuru County - May 28, 2026", "incidentStatistics": ["16 confirmed fatalities (students)", "79 injured students requiring medical attention", "220 students in the dormitory when the fire started", "Response time: First responders arrived approximately 2 hours after the fire was reported", "School Fire Context (Kenya)", "2024: 21 boys killed in a dormitory fire at Hillside Endarasha Academy, Nyeri County", "2017: 10 students died in a dormitory fire at Moi Girls High School in Nairobi", "2001: 67 students died in the deadliest school fire in Kenya''s history at Kyanguli Secondary School", "2022 Auditor General Report: Found most state secondary schools were not prepared to deal with fires"], "phases": [{"phase": "PHASE 1", "body": "1. Dispatch & Response Assessment:\n\nYour Response: (fill in)\n\ntext\nTime to scene (estimated distance 30 km): ________________________________\nInitial patient count estimate: __________________________________________\nResources you are bringing: _____________________________________________\nWhat additional resources should be requested immediately? _______________\n2. Safety & Scene Considerations:\n\nYour Response: (fill in)\n\ntext\nSafety concerns: ________________________________________________________\nBSI precautions: ________________________________________________________\nTriage considerations: __________________________________________________\nPart 2: Arrival at Scene\nYou arrive at the school approximately 45 minutes after dispatch. The scene is chaotic: \n\nFire: The dormitory fire is still burning. Three fire engines are on scene but have difficulty accessing the building.\n\nStudents: Injured students are everywhere. Some are lying on the ground, others are being carried by teachers and fellow students.\n\nParents: Dozens of parents have already arrived, frantically searching for their children.\n\nSecurity: Police have established a perimeter, but it is not fully secure.\n\nOther Responders: Kenya Red Cross personnel are on scene but appear overwhelmed.\n\nPatients observed:\n\nPatient\tAge/Sex\tInjuries\tStatus\n1\t15/F\tBurns to arms and face, singed hair, RR 30, HR 110\tConscious, in severe distress\n2\t17/F\tBurn injuries to >50% of body, RR 36, HR 140, BP 85/50\tSemi-conscious, severe respiratory distress\n3\t16/F\tFractured leg from jumping, open fracture tibia, RR 22, HR 110\tConscious, in pain, BP 110/70\n4\t16/F\tUnresponsive, not breathing, visible burns\tApneic, pulseless\n5\t18/F\tSmoke inhalation, coughing, O2 sat 90%, RR 30\tConscious, anxious\n6\t15/F\tMultiple lacerations from glass, bleeding, RR 24, HR 100\tConscious, BP 110/70\n7\t17/F\tSecond-degree burns to both hands, RR 25, HR 115\tConscious, anxious\n\ud83d\uded1"}, {"phase": "PHASE 2", "body": "3. Triage & Initial Assessment:\n\nYour Response: (fill in)\n\ntext\nPatient 1 (15/F, burns to arms/face, RR 30, HR 110):\nColor: _______________ Priority: _______________\nInterventions: ___________________________________________________________\n\nPatient 2 (17/F, >50% burns, RR 36, HR 140, BP 85/50):\nColor: _______________ Priority: _______________\nInterventions: ___________________________________________________________\n\nPatient 3 (16/F, open fracture tibia, RR 22, HR 110):\nColor: _______________ Priority: _______________\nInterventions: ___________________________________________________________\n\nPatient 4 (16/F, unresponsive, apneic, pulseless):\nColor: _______________ Priority: _______________\nInterventions: ___________________________________________________________\n\nPatient 5 (18/F, smoke inhalation, RR 30, O2 sat 90%):\nColor: _______________ Priority: _______________\nInterventions: ___________________________________________________________\n\nPatient 6 (15/F, lacerations, RR 24, HR 100):\nColor: _______________ Priority: _______________\nInterventions: ___________________________________________________________\n\nPatient 7 (17/F, hand burns, RR 25, HR 115):\nColor: _______________ Priority: _______________\nInterventions: ___________________________________________________________\n4. Critical Decision: Burn Triage:\n\nYour Response: (fill in)\n\ntext\nFor Patient 2 (17/F, >50% burns, BP 85/50, RR 36):\n- Rule of Nines estimate: ________________________________________________\n- Critical burn criteria: ________________________________________________\n- Transport priority: ____________________________________________________\n- Most likely complications: _____________________________________________\n\nFor Patient 7 (17/F, hand burns):\n- Burn severity: ________________________________________________________\n- Critical burn? Why/why not: ___________________________________________\n- Special considerations: ________________________________________________\n\ud83d\udcca"}], "evaluation": [{"phase": "Phase 1", "component": "Dispatch Assessment", "points": 10, "criteria": "Correct identification of response needs"}, {"phase": "Phase 1", "component": "Safety Considerations", "points": 10, "criteria": "Appropriate scene safety protocols"}, {"phase": "Phase 2", "component": "Triage Accuracy", "points": 15, "criteria": "Correct START triage classification"}, {"phase": "Phase 2", "component": "Burn Triage", "points": 10, "criteria": "Accurate burn severity assessment"}, {"phase": "Phase 3", "component": "Transport Planning", "points": 15, "criteria": "Effective resource allocation"}, {"phase": "Phase 3", "component": "Communication", "points": 10, "criteria": "Appropriate hospital notification"}, {"phase": "Phase 4", "component": "Lessons Learned", "points": 10, "criteria": "Insightful analysis of failures"}], "competencies": ["Scene Safety", "Mass Casualty Management", "Pediatric Emergencies", "Communication", "EMS Operations"]}'::jsonb, 2, 75, true)
